&lt;p&gt;Now, launch it, click on the filter icon and enable the &lt;code&gt;Show Runtimes&lt;/code&gt; option in order to see the drivers currently installed on your system.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;






&lt;figure&gt;
    &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; alt=&#34;Warehouse&#34; src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/s7aEmPu.png&#34;&gt;

  
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once that&amp;rsquo;s done, close filter window, scroll down the list until you see the &lt;strong&gt;nVidia&lt;/strong&gt; drivers, click on the 3 vertical dots and select the &lt;strong&gt;Disable Updates&lt;/strong&gt; option. That&amp;rsquo;s it ! Now they will never be updated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Downgrade Drivers 
    &lt;div id=&#34;downgrade-drivers&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This, in my opinion is the most likely scenario to happen to most users who are new to &lt;strong&gt;Linux&lt;/strong&gt; as a whole. It&amp;rsquo;s the one where drivers get updated without previously having &amp;ldquo;Pinned&amp;rdquo; them. If that happens to you, and you end up with a black screen, fear not there is a solution. It&amp;rsquo;s called &lt;em&gt;Downgrading&lt;/em&gt;. We will be using a tool called, you guessed it, &lt;strong&gt;Downgrade&lt;/strong&gt;. More info in article below.&lt;/p&gt;





  


